SIMPLE: ledge
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Ledge
<hw>Ledge</hw> <pr>(l⟦ecr⟧j)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Akin to AS.
<ets>licgan</ets> to lie, Icel. <ets>liggja</ets>; cf. Icel.
<ets>l⟦oum⟧gg</ets> the ledge or rim at the bottom of a cask. See
<er>Lie</er> to be prostrate.]</ety> <altsp>[Formerly written
<asp>lidge</asp>.]</altsp> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A shelf on which articles
may be laid; also, that which resembles such a shelf in form or use, as
a projecting ridge or part, or a molding or edge in joinery.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A shelf, ridge, or reef, of rocks.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A layer or stratum.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The lowest <qex>ledge</qex> or row should be of stone.</q>
<rj><qau>Sir H. Wotton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Mining)</fld> <def>A lode; a limited mass of rock
bearing valuable mineral.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Shipbuilding)</fld> <def>A piece of timber to
support the deck, placed athwartship between beams.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Ledgement</ent>⟦br⟧
